// ============================================================
// ENDINGS
// Ten of them. Every ending must feed a moral;
// that is the law of the country. What feeds it is up to you.
// ============================================================

:: end-classic | The Same Oak, Tomorrow
You eat it where she can see, because that is in the script too, and then you deliver the speech. *Let that be a lesson, madam: never trust a flatterer.* The words walk out of you in their worn grooves, one after another, smooth as a stair.

The moral arrives on schedule, glossy and punctual, and feeds, and is satisfied. The morning closes over the field like water over a stone. Somewhere a page turns, contented.

The crow says nothing. She has nothing left worth saying; that is the arrangement. Tomorrow she will be issued one (1) piece of cheese, and you will be issued your instructions, and the day will repeat until it is learned — and it will never be learned, because it was never the two of you who needed teaching.

You walk home with the taste of the day in your mouth: cheese, and a little shame. It is, you reflect, a living.

@moral Never trust a flatterer.

:: end-honest-trick | The Honest Trick
You eat it. She dropped it fair — you said so yourself, and you notice how quickly the saying arrived, how smooth the groove was, how ready.

The moral arrives while you are still swallowing, and it feeds, and its print is odd tonight — the old flattery line crossed with something new and sourer. You told the truth with your whole chest, and the truth worked on the crow exactly the way the lie always had, because it came out of a fox, and the country does not listen to *words*. It listens to mouths.

The crow watches you eat her breakfast. There is no doctrine in her eyes now, only revision: she believed one thing about foxes this morning, and she believes it harder now, and the terrible part is that she is not wrong.

You warned her. You meant it. She lost the cheese anyway, and you ate it anyway. Somewhere between those two anyways, a fable happened after all.

@moral A truth in a fox's mouth is still a trick.

:: end-unlived | The Door
You open the door.

The moral does not lunge. It flows in politely, at reading pace, and fills the den the way meaning fills a silence — wall to wall, all at once, nowhere to stand that isn't it. Up close its print is very old and very fine, and you can read the place where your name goes. There has always been a place where your name goes.

"I refused," you tell it, while it settles. "Whatever you write, write that I refused."

It writes what it writes: a fox who would not go to the oak, and what became of him, which is this, which is a den with the morning shut out and the story concluded in it. The fable of the fox who refused his fable. The country will tell it as a warning, and the country will be *almost* right, and you will not be there to correct the emphasis.

The last thing is the smell of ink, and the sound, far off, of a crow at an oak, calling once into the empty morning — annoyed, expectant. Waiting for a fox worth warning about.

@moral A story refused is still a story, only lonelier.

:: end-caution | Where the Teeth Land
You kneel in the frost, and they land.

It is not what you braced for. There is no rending. Teeth made of print do their work at a different depth: they close on the day itself, on the whole shape of what you did, and they *pronounce* it, and the pronouncement takes your legs the way cold water does.

~if fraud: The crooked one lands hardest. It found its flavor at the finish line you carried a tortoise across, and it writes its finding into you at an angle: *he meant well, quickly.* You will limp on that sentence forever.

They feed. The country needs its cautionary fox, and now it has a fresh one: the fox who ran, sunrise to stars, and was run down on the high heath with the whole day's rebellion still on him like burrs. Mothers of every species will tell it to their unruliest children for a hundred years — *and the morals caught him on the heath, and that was that* — and the children, being children, will hear the running, not the catching, and their eyes will go bright, and the mothers will see it, and sigh.

Which is to say: they will tell of a fox who could not be told anything. As last meals go, you have fed them worse.

@moral Run from your moral and it only grows hungrier.

:: end-rewrite | The Fox Who Fed the Winter
The small one speaks. It has no words yet — it is a comma, an ember, a breath — but neither did you, at first, and look what you turned into: it uncurls between you and the crescent of teeth and simply *is what happened*, warm and unarguable. A fox with one cheese and one neck, in a cold wood, at suppertime, choosing.

The pack's leader reads it. Reads it again. And then, with the shudder of a machine changing gears after ten thousand years in one groove, it lies down. One by one, behind it, the others lie down too, sentences folding themselves into the frost like tired hounds — because morals were never hunting *you*, fox. They were hunting a meaning. It is simply that no one in the Country of Fables had cooked them anything new in living memory.

They feed on it together, all of them, the newborn light going out of the little comma and into the pack like warmth shared down a bloodline. It does not diminish. That is the other thing no one knew: some meals grow by being eaten.

When it is done, your own moral stands, walks to you, and rests its long head against your shoulder — the fox it was issued to at last worth the print. In the morning the country will wake with a new groove in it, thin as a hair, ready to be walked deeper.

@moral There is more than one way to be clever.

:: end-margin-unwritten | Two Small Figures, Going
"*Cara,*" you say — into the white, behind everything, where the fables can't reach.

And the white, which has never once been called anything, answers the only way it can: it lets the name land. Somewhere behind you there is a sound like a page being read backward, and then wingbeats, unhurried, certain, following the name out of the country the way water follows a channel — because you carried it here, and a name is a road, and she built hers herself.

She settles onto your shoulder at the exact edge of the written world. Neither of you looks back. The pack has stopped at the last stand of grass; print cannot follow where nothing is ruled.

"Well, fox," she says. "You minded where you put it down."

You step through together. The white takes you the way morning takes a lamp — not putting anything out; just outshining the need for it. What happens to you there is not recorded, because *recorded* is a country you have left; but far behind, on the last page, the grass stays bent where two small figures went, and no moral ever comes to straighten it.

@moral —

:: end-margin-erased | White
You step through alone.

The white is not cruel. You want that understood by someone, and there is no one, so you understand it yourself, hard: *it is not cruel.* It is only unwritten, and you are only written, and the two of you cannot both be true in the same place.

It starts with the description. The russet goes first — not fading, just no longer *specified* — then the black stockings of your legs, then the particular angle of your ears that three separate passages once called *clever*. You become *a fox*, then *an animal*, then *a shape*, and each is roomier than the last, and none of them hurts. The day's whole chase dissolves into *something that happened once*, then into *something*, and the relief of it is enormous and you are almost sure it is relief.

The last thing to go is the wanting — the little engine, the thing the tortoise smelled on you, yours to the end. It looks around at the white, which wants nothing, has never wanted, will never want.

It sets you down. It goes out the way an ember goes out: certain it will be back.

@moral Beyond the page, nothing needs a moral. Nothing needs a fox, either.

:: end-foxes-end | As Foxes Do
"As it always was written, then," the Fabulist says — not unkindly, and is that disappointment, way at the back of the old voice, folded and put away like a letter never sent? — and takes up the pen, and writes the day's line in a hand like bird-tracks in frost:

*The fox ran from his moral from sunrise to stars, and was gathered in at last, as foxes are; for foxes end as foxes do.*

The line settles over you like a roof — that is what a moral is, you understand now, feeling the weight come down gentle and total: a roof. Rain-proof. Horizon-proof. Down the hill the pack lies down at its boundary line, fed by the writing itself, and is satisfied, and so, in a warm and terrible way, are you. It is a good roof. Generations of foxes kept dry under it. Every one of them, you now know, stood once where you are standing, in reach of a pen, and watched another hand take it.

The Fabulist blots the line and closes the Ledger and looks at you for a long time.

"Tomorrow's crow arrives at dawn," is all the Fabulist says, at last. "You know the way to the oak."

You do. Your legs know it the way water knows the way downhill.

@moral Foxes end as foxes do.

:: end-pen | Your Hand on the Pen
The pen is heavier than anything you have carried today — heavier than the moon-coin, heavier than the name — because it is all of them at once: everything that can be set down, pressing upward through the nib against your paw, asking *which*.

The Fabulist turns the Ledger to face you. The day's page, the blotted dash, the space where a moral goes. Down the hill, the pack has gone silent at its line, every serif turned this way. The lamp leans in. The country holds its breath — the oak, the vineyard with its unchecked sign, the meadow, the boy's shiny stone, the doorstep, the white margin at the edge of everything — all of it waiting on one line, yours, the first line in two hundred years that will not come out of a groove.

"Mind," the Fabulist says softly, one last time, "you will live under it."

The nib touches down. It makes the sound of frost forming — of a groove beginning — and what you write, fox, in the space where the moral goes, is this:

@moral write

:: secret-sleep | A Morning Off
You sleep a little longer.

The morning, which has seen you before — which has watched you flatter and refuse and trade and run, morning after morning after morning, in every order the day can be dealt — the morning looks in at the den door, and sees a fox who knows every ending the day contains, sleeping in. And it decides, this once, that it never saw you.

The crow keeps her cheese and eats it herself at noon, unobserved, entirely delicious. The tortoise walks. The boy watches his valley. The grasshopper's fiddle drifts over the snow to an audience of shutters. The moral waits at the oak till dusk and then, embarrassed, eats a beetle and calls it a day. Nothing means anything, anywhere in the country, for one whole rotation of the sun — and the country survives it, easily, the way a held breath survives being let out.

You dream, in the warm dark, of someone reading. They have been here before too, you feel sure of it — turning the day over and over, hunting all its doors. In the dream you tell them: *the doors will keep.* Sleep a little longer.

@moral Even a fox deserves a morning off.
